{"parentUuid":"a8d92227-d4f1-418c-99b8-0cb3c63c2908","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adc6e872310c3ca7e","message":{"id":"resp_08115acb868cc7c80169b9a1e4d3ec819a8042c6dda2626179","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"gpt-5.4","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_K0F2w1hSPhceBeEXRABgrI95","name":"mcp__sequential-thinking__sequentialthinking","input":{"thought":"I need to compare four roadmap-pipeline improvement items against three later refactor specs, focusing on fail-closed/fail-safe semantics, StepStatus compatibility, and executor/prompts/generate-pipeline interactions. First I will gather the assigned file and the three specs, then classify each item with evidence and a keep/revise/remove recommendation.","thoughtNumber":1,"totalThoughts":4,"nextThoughtNeeded":true}}],"stop_reason":null},"type":"assistant","uuid":"ac04c3af-cb77-4cd3-9cb5-9bf5143d8351","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:48:20.493Z","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"17b9e3b1-6afc-4783-ad4f-83b4bdcdd7d6","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adc6e872310c3ca7e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_TPPU26RGaDBLkCCetIbYG2g6","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The following code sections were retrieved:\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-roadmap-pipeline.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: roadmap-pipeline\n     3\tdeliverable: D-0026\n     4\tsource_comparison: comparison-roadmap-pipeline.md\n     5\tverdict: split by context\n     6\tprinciple_primary: Restartability\n     7\tprinciple_secondary: Bounded Complexity\n     8\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n     9\t---\n    10\t\n    11\t# Improvement Plan: Roadmap Pipeline\n    12\t\n    13\tTraceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles: Evidence Integrity (P1-E), Deterministic Gates (P1-D), Restartability (P1-R), Bounded Complexity (P1-B), Scalable Quality Enforcement (P1-Q).\n    14\t\n    15\t---\n    16\t\n    17\t## ITEM RP-001 — Fail-Closed Gate Semantics in execute_roadmap\n...\n    24\t\n    25\t**File paths and change description**:\n    26\t- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` — In `execute_roadmap()`, verify that any gate result that is not an affirmative PASS is treated as FAIL. Review calls to `gate_passed()` to confirm no PASS-with-conditions path exists. Annotate the gate call site with a comment: `# fail-closed: inconclusive result is FAIL per D-0022 Principle 2`.\n    27\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/gates.py` — Confirm `gate_passed()` returns `(False, reason)` for all non-PASS paths including timeouts and parse failures (not just criteria mismatches).\n    28\t\n    29\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 2 (Deterministic Gates), direction 1: \"When a gate evaluation cannot definitively confirm PASS, the result is FAIL — not PASS with caveats.\" This prevents partial completion from being mistaken for success.\n    30\t\n    31\t**Dependencies**: None (prerequisite for RP-003)\n    32\t**Acceptance criteria**: `gate_passed()` returns `(False, ...)` for empty output files, malformed YAML, and timeout conditions; no call site in executor.py treats a non-PASS as a soft warning.\n    33\t**Risk**: Low. Purely clarifying semantics; existing logic already returns False in error cases; change is annotation + explicit timeout handling.\n    34\t\n    35\t---\n    36\t\n    37\t## ITEM RP-002 — Documented Fallback Degradation Path\n...\n    64\t\n    65\t**File paths and change description**:\n    66\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/models.py` — Extend `StepStatus` enum to include: `PENDING`, `IN_PROGRESS`, `DONE`, `FAILED`, `SKIPPED` (matching LW's state formalism). Confirm that `StepResult` exposes the status via its `status` field.\n    67\t- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` — In `_build_steps()`, ensure each Step is constructed with `status=StepStatus.PENDING` at creation, transitions to `IN_PROGRESS` during execution, and `DONE` or `FAILED` after gate evaluation. This makes the state machine explicit and forward-compatible with future multi-track scenarios.\n    68\t- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` — Update `_apply_resume()` to read `StepStatus.DONE` (not just gate_passed history) as the skip criterion for resumed steps.\n    69\t\n    70\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 3 (Restartability), direction 3: \"The step-level states in StepResult should be extended to match [per-track state machine] formalism for forward compatibility.\"\n    71\t\n    72\t**Dependencies**: RP-001 (gate_passed semantics must be settled before DONE/FAILED transition logic is implemented)\n    73\t**Acceptance criteria**: `StepStatus` enum has all 5 states; a step that fails its gate transitions to FAILED not remains IN_PROGRESS; `--resume` skips DONE steps only.\n    74\t**Risk**: Medium. Model changes may affect serialization to `.roadmap-state.json`; require compatibility test.\n    75\t\n    76\t---\n    77\t\n    78\t## ITEM RP-004 — Hard Resource Caps Formalization\n    79\t\n    80\t**Priority**: P2\n    81\t**Effort**: S\n    82\t**Classification**: add new code\n    83\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's track-cap principle (5 tracks / 15 agents) as IC-native configuration constants, not LW's Rigorflow runtime scheduler\n    84\t**Why not full import**: LW's track and agent caps are enforced by a complex Rigorflow runtime scheduler with dynamic load balancing; IC needs only configuration constants with validation at CLI entry point.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-pipeline-analysis.md\n...\n    48\t\n    49\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 7: \"IC's diagnostic output should distinguish between sprint CLI failures (framework issues) and task specification failures (project issues).\"\n    50\t\n    51\t**Dependencies**: PA-001 (pre-packaged artifacts include the gate output context needed to classify framework vs. project)\n    52\t**Acceptance criteria**: `DiagnosticReport` has `failure_source` field with three allowed values; stage 4 summary includes the failure_source prominently; test verifying that a .md input failure is classified as \"project\" and a pipeline step exception is classified as \"framework.\"\n    53\t**Risk**: Low. Additive field; classification logic is deterministic based on input type.\n    54\t\n    55\t---\n    56\t\n    57\t## ITEM PA-003 — 4-Category Failure Classification in DiagnosticReport\n    58\t\n    59\t**Priority**: P1\n    60\t**Effort**: S\n    61\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    62\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's 4-category failure taxonomy (execution, template, evidence, workflow failures) as a structured output field in IC's DiagnosticReport, not LW's point-based scoring system\n    63\t**Why not full import**: LW's failure classification uses a point-based confidence scoring system (High ≥5 pts, Medium 3-4, Low ≤2) tied to its batch execution model; IC needs only the four-category labels plus the confidence level concept as a simplified tier (High/Medium/Low based on evidence count, not point arithmetic).\n    64\t\n    65\t**File paths and change description**:\n    66\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — Add `FailureCategory` enum: `EXECUTION_FAILURE`, `TEMPLATE_FAILURE`, `EVIDENCE_FAILURE`, `WORKFLOW_FAILURE`. Add `failure_categories: list[tuple[FailureCategory, ConfidenceLevel]]` to `DiagnosticReport` where `ConfidenceLevel` is `HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW`.\n    67\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — In the analysis stages, classify each identified failure into one of the four categories. `EXECUTION_FAILURE`: model refused, output truncated, timeout. `TEMPLATE_FAILURE`: output does not match expected gate schema. `EVIDENCE_FAILURE`: missing file:line citations, CEV violations. `WORKFLOW_FAILURE`: stage skipped, gate evaluation bypassed.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-pm-agent.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: pm-agent\n     3\tframework: IronClaude\n     4\tphase: 3\n     5\tgenerated: 2026-03-14\n     6\tevidence_source: auggie-mcp\n     7\t---\n     8\t\n     9\t# Strategy: IronClaude PM Agent\n    10\t\n    11\t## 1. Design Philosophy\n    12\t\n    13\tThe PM Agent exists to reduce wrong-direction work and post-implementation rework through three orthogonal quality patterns: pre-execution confidence gating, post-implementation evidence validation, and cross-session error learning. The core design decision is to implement these as **importable Python classes** rather than pure Markdown behavioral prompts, enabling testability via pytest fixtures and programmatic integration.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-adversarial-pipeline.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: adversarial-pipeline\n     3\tframework: IronClaude\n     4\tphase: 3\n     5\tgenerated: 2026-03-14\n     6\tevidence_source: auggie-mcp\n     7\t---\n     8\t\n     9\t# Strategy: IronClaude Adversarial Pipeline\n    10\t\n    11\t## 1. Design Philosophy\n    12\t\n    13\tThe adversarial pipeline exists to produce higher-quality artifacts than any single model can generate by systematically exploiting model diversity: generating multiple variants with different model/persona configurations, then comparing them through structured debate, hybrid scoring, and evidence-tracked merging. The core design principle is **structured disagreement as a quality signal** — divergence between variants reveals assumptions and trade-offs that converged single-model output suppresses.\n...\n    26\t\n    27\t**5-step sequential protocol** (each step produces a named artifact):\n    28\t1. **Diff Analysis** → `diff-analysis.md`: Structural comparison (section ordering, hierarchy), content comparison (claim-level), and contradiction detection across all variants.\n    29\t2. **Adversarial Debate** → `debate-transcript.md`: Per-point debate rounds where domain agents argue for their variant's approach. Convergence tracked as `agreed_points / total_diff_points`; threshold configurable (default 0.80). Round 2.5 (invariant probe) activates at `--depth standard|deep`. Max rounds: 1 (quick), 2 (standard), 3 (deep).\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-adversarial-pipeline.md\n...\n    61\t\n    62\t**Priority**: P1\n    63\t**Effort**: S\n    64\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    65\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's 4-category failure classification taxonomy (execution failures, template failures, evidence failures, workflow failures) as a classification layer for adversarial debate failure modes, not LW's point-based scoring with confidence tiers\n    66\t**Why not full import**: LW's full failure classification uses a confidence scoring system (High ≥5 pts, Medium 3-4, Low ≤2) tied to its batch execution model; IC's adversarial pipeline needs only the four-category taxonomy as a structural classifier for debate outputs, without point scoring.\n    67\t\n    68\t**File paths and change description**:\n    69\t- `.claude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Add a \"Failure Mode Classification\" section with the four categories: (1) Execution failures (model refused, output truncated, agent timeout), (2) Template failures (output does not match artifact schema), (3) Evidence failures (claims without file:line citations, CEV violations), (4) Workflow failures (pipeline stage skipped, convergence plateau not detected). When a debate round produces an artifact with failures, classify each failure before scoring.\n    70\t- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Sync copy.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/comparison-roadmap-pipeline.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomparison_pair: 1\n     3\tic_component: Roadmap Pipeline\n     4\tlw_component: Pipeline Orchestration (Rigorflow)\n     5\tic_source: src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py, src/superclaude/skills/sc-roadmap-protocol/SKILL.md\n     6\tlw_source: .claude/commands/rf/pipeline.md\n     7\tmapping_type: functional_analog\n     8\tverdict_class: split by context\n     9\tconfidence: 0.82\n    10\tpatterns_not_mass_verified: true\n    11\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n    12\t---\n    13\t\n    14\t# Adversarial Comparison: Roadmap Pipeline (IC) vs Pipeline Orchestration (LW)\n    15\t\n    16\t## 1. Debating Positions\n    17\t\n    18\t### IC Advocate Position\n    19\tThe IronClaude roadmap pipeline employs a **deterministic, file-on-disk 9-step sequential pipeline** with explicit gate validation at every step. Each artifact is independently reviewable and the pipeline is resumable via `.roadmap-state.json` with stale-spec hash detection. The dual-agent generate strategy (parallel `generate-a` + `generate-b`) is a direct quality mechanism: by forcing two independent LLM variants and running adversarial debate (step 4), IC surfaces assumptions that a single-model generation suppresses. Critically, **the pipeline is implemented in Python — not bash, not experimental infrastructure**. It runs on any standard Python environment with no special flags.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improvement-backlog.md\n...\n    21\t\n    22\tThis document is produced in accordance with the `/sc:roadmap` ingestion schema pre-validated in `artifacts/D-0030/spec.md`. All 31 items conform to the extraction pipeline requirements: behavioral change descriptions (FR-extractable), explicit priority signals (P0/P1/P2), acceptance criteria (success_criteria), risk statements (risks field), and dependency references (dependencies field). Zero schema incompatibilities per D-0030.\n    23\t\n    24\tSource document: `artifacts/D-0034/spec.md` (final-improve-plan.md — Phase 8 validated, SC-007 PASS)\n    25\t\n    26\t---\n    27\t\n    28\t## Priority P0 — Gate Integrity (13 items)\n    29\t\n    30\t### RP-001 — Fail-Closed Gate Semantics in execute_roadmap\n    31\t\n    32\t**Priority**: P0\n    33\t**Effort**: S\n    34\t**Component**: Roadmap Pipeline\n    35\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-roadmap-pipeline.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: roadmap-pipeline\n     3\tframework: IronClaude\n     4\tphase: 3\n     5\tgenerated: 2026-03-14\n     6\tevidence_source: auggie-mcp\n     7\t---\n     8\t\n     9\t# Strategy: IronClaude Roadmap Pipeline\n    10\t\n    11\t## 1. Design Philosophy\n    12\t\n    13\tThe roadmap pipeline exists to eliminate LLM output variance when generating project roadmaps from specifications. The core design decision is to treat roadmap generation as a structured, multi-step pipeline with file-on-disk artifacts between steps — rather than a single large prompt — because each artifact acts as both a quality gate input and a resume checkpoint.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md\n...\n   502\t    min_lines=10,\n   503\t    enforcement_tier=\"STRICT\",\n   504\t    semantic_checks=[\n   505\t        SemanticCheck(\n   506\t            name=\"analysis_complete_true\",\n   507\t            check_fn=_analysis_complete_true,\n   508\t            failure_message=\"analysis_complete must be true\",\n   509\t        ),\n   510\t        SemanticCheck(\n   511\t            name=\"zero_unwired_callables\",\n   512\t            check_fn=_zero_unwired_callables,\n   513\t            failure_message=\"unwired_count must be 0; all injectable callables must be provided\",\n   514\t        ),\n   515\t        SemanticCheck(\n   516\t            name=\"zero_orphan_modules\",\n   517\t            check_fn=_zero_orphan_modules,\n   518\t            failure_message=\"orphan_count must be 0; all exported functions must have importers\",\n   519\t        ),\n   520\t        SemanticCheck(\n   521\t            name=\"zero_unwired_registries\",\n   522\t            check_fn=_zero_unwired_registries,\n   523\t            failure_message=\"registry_count must be 0; all registry entries must resolve\",\n   524\t        ),\n...\n   552\t\n   553\tif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"shadow\":\n   554\t    # Log result but do not affect task status\n   555\t    logger.info(f\"[shadow] Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   556\telif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"soft\":\n   557\t    # Warn in TUI but do not block\n   558\t    if not report.passed:\n   559\t        tui.warn(f\"Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   560\telif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"full\":\n   561\t    # Block task completion\n   562\t    passed, reason = gate_passed(wiring_report_path, WIRING_GATE)\n   563\t    if not passed:\n   564\t        # Trigger remediation via SprintGatePolicy\n   565\t        ...\n   566\t```\n...\n   689\t\n   690\t| Field | Type | Constraint |\n   691\t|-------|------|-----------|\n   692\t| `gate` | string | Must be `\"wiring-verification\"` |\n   693\t| `target_dir` | string | Non-empty |\n   694\t| `files_analyzed` | int | >= 0 |\n   695\t| `unwired_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   696\t| `orphan_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   697\t| `registry_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   698\t| `total_findings` | int | Must equal sum of above three |\n   699\t| `analysis_complete` | bool | Must be true |\n   700\t| `whitelist_entries_applied` | int | >= 0; count of whitelist entries that suppressed findings |\n   701\t\n   702\t---\n   703\t\n   704\t## 7. Risk Assessment\n...\n   867\t\n   868\t| SC | Description | Verification |\n   869\t|----|-------------|-------------|\n   870\t| SC-001 | Wiring gate detects `Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at call site | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_callable_basic` |\n   871\t| SC-002 | Wiring gate detects orphan modules in `steps/` directories | Unit test: `test_detect_orphan_module` |\n   872\t| SC-003 | Wiring gate detects unresolvable registry entries | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_registry` |\n   873\t| SC-004 | Report conforms to `GateCriteria` validation pattern | Unit test: `test_gate_passes_clean_report` |\n   874\t| SC-005 | `gate_passed()` evaluates `WIRING_GATE` without modification | Integration test: `test_cli_portify_fixture` |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md\n...\n   110\t\n   111\tA deterministic, regex-based post-generation pass that scans the merged roadmap for scaffolding terms and verifies each has a corresponding discharge task in a later phase. Catches the failure mode where early phases use \"mocked\", \"stub\", \"skeleton\", \"placeholder\" language that creates implicit obligations that later phases never fulfill.\n   112\t\n   113\t### Detection Axis\n   114\t\n   115\tV2-A's obligation scanner detects a fundamentally different failure mode than omission-based approaches. Rather than checking whether a requirement is present, it checks whether deferred commitments are fulfilled. This catches bugs where the requirement IS mentioned (as scaffolding) but the follow-through is missing.\n   116\t\n   117\t### Implementation\n...\n   947\t\n   948\t### Enforcement Strategy\n   949\t\n   950\t<!-- Source: V1-C (spec structural audit), adapted per refactor-plan -->\n   951\t\n   952\tPhase 1 (immediate): Warning-only. The executor logs a warning if the ratio falls below 0.5 but does not block the pipeline. This allows shadow-mode validation on real specs before enforcement.\n   953\t\n   954\tPhase 2 (after validation): STRICT enforcement. If the structural count suggests the extraction is missing significant content, the executor re-triggers extraction or halts with an actionable error.\n   955\t\n   956\t---\n   957\t\n   958\t## 8. Gate Definition\n   959\t\n   960\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n   961\t\n   962\t### New Gate: `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`\n   963\t\n   964\t**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` (modify existing)\n   965\t\n   966\t```python\n   967\t# --- Anti-Instinct Gate check functions ---\n...\n   999\t\n  1000\t\n  1001\tdef _fingerprint_coverage_check(content: str) -> bool:\n  1002\t    \"\"\"Verify spec code-level identifiers have sufficient roadmap coverage.\n  1003\t\n  1004\t    This check requires both spec and roadmap content. Since semantic\n  1005\t    checks receive only a single content string, the real enforcement\n  1006\t    happens in the executor. This validates the executor's written result.\n  1007\t    \"\"\"\n  1008\t    fm = _parse_frontmatter(content)\n  1009\t    if fm is None:\n  1010\t        return False\n  1011\t    try:\n  1012\t        return float(fm.get(\"fingerprint_coverage\", 0.0)) >= 0.7\n  1013\t    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n  1014\t        return False\n  1015\t\n  1016\t\n  1017\t# --- Gate definition ---\n  1018\t\n  1019\tANTI_INSTINCT_GATE = GateCriteria(\n  1020\t    required_frontmatter_fields=[\n  1021\t        \"undischarged_obligations\",    # V2-A: integer count\n  1022\t        \"uncovered_contracts\",         # V5-1: integer count\n  1023\t        \"fingerprint_coverage\",        # V4-2: float 0.0-1.0\n  1024\t    ],\n  1025\t    min_lines=10,\n  1026\t    enforcement_tier=\"STRICT\",\n  1027\t    semantic_checks=[\n  1028\t        SemanticCheck(\n  1029\t            name=\"no_undischarged_obligations\",\n  1030\t            check_fn=_no_undischarged_obligations,\n  1031\t            failure_message=(\n  1032\t                \"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected: early-phase \"\n  1033\t                \"mocks/stubs/skeletons have no corresponding replace/integrate/\"\n  1034\t                \"wire task in later phases\"\n  1035\t            ),\n  1036\t        ),\n  1037\t    "}]}]},"uuid":"fd2c9b29-07d4-4450-ba4a-6517465ce099","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:48:23.986Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"17b9e3b1-6afc-4783-ad4f-83b4bdcdd7d6","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
