r = PortifyExecutor(\n    43→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:63:return executor.run()\n    44→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:76:| `step_runner` / `_execute_step()` | `executor.py:323, 393-415` | `cli_portify/executor.py` | Never | All 12 portify steps no-op with exit code 0 |\n    45→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:77:| `DEVIATION_ANALYSIS_GATE` | `roadmap/gates.py:712-758` | `roadmap/gates.py` | `_build_steps()` in `roadmap/executor.py` never adds a `deviation-analysis` step | Gate object exists; `ALL_GATES` references it; roadmap pipeline never runs it |\n    46→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:78:| `SprintGatePolicy` / `TrailingGateRunner` | `sprint/executor.py:47-90`, `pipeline/trailing_gate.py` | Both modules imported | `execute_sprint()` never instantiates `TrailingGateRunner` or `SprintGatePolicy` | Trailing gate infrastructure silently inactive for all sprint runs |\n    47→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:107:`roadmap/executor.py` (Tier-A importer). Dead code detection would exclude it. But the `DEVIATION_ANALYSIS_GATE`\n    48→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:184:  Class:      PortifyExecutor (cli_portify/executor.py:315)\n    49→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:186:  No-op at:   executor.py:397 — else branch returns (0, \"\", False)\n    50→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:188:    - executor.py:1395 — PortifyExecutor(steps=..., workdir=..., dry_run=...) — step_runner ABSENT\n    51→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:201:`analyze_workflow.py`, etc. are never imported by `cli_portify/executor.py`, `commands.py`, or\n    52→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:318:  File:    cli_portify/executor.py:397-399\n    53→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:322:  Also at: executor.py:408-411 (retry path — same pattern)\n    54→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:333:**Archetypal case**: `STEP_REGISTRY` in `executor.py` is a `dict[str, dict]` mapping step IDs to\n    55→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:335:reference or import. The registry provides step configuration for the executor loop but does not\n    56→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:372:  Registry: STEP_REGISTRY (cli_portify/executor.py)\n    57→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:412:| Module imported by executor but functions never called | Does not catch | **Catches** (REGC, CPC) |\n    58→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:469:| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` | Wire `INTEGRATION_GATE` into `_build_steps()` as a new step after `spec-fidelity` (also resolves the DEVIATION_ANALYSIS_GATE wiring gap if that step is added simultaneously) |\n    59→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:484:- Run in the preflight executor before any sprint step begins\n    60→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:541:| NOPF | `executor.py:397-399` and `executor.py:408-411` — no-op returning `(0, \"\", False)` | ERROR | Yes |\n    61→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:560:- IRE applies: `SprintGatePolicy` is defined in `sprint/executor.py` and `TrailingGateRunner` is\n    62→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:577:3. **NOPF test**: Source text containing the exact `executor.py:397-399` pattern → NOPF finds\n    63→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:643:**Example**: `executor = ExecutorFactory.create(config)` where the factory internally passes\n    64→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-03-code-integration-gate.md:686:| `_build_steps()` integration in `roadmap/executor.py` | 0.5 days | New step definition, output path, gate assignment |\n    65→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:38:This assumption breaks in the presence of a no-op executor. The forensic report (`cli-portify-executor-noop-forensic-report.md`, §1) shows that `PortifyExecutor._execute_step()` contains:\n    66→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:46:When `step_runner` is `None` (the production default), every step returns `(0, \"\", False)` regardless of what real implementation exists in `steps/`. The executor then writes `return-contract.yaml` listing all 12 steps as completed with `outcome: SUCCESS`. This single file satisfies the only artifact existence check that runs: the cli-portify pipeline verifies `return-contract.yaml` exists and contains `outcome: SUCCESS`. Both conditions are true. The gate system approves the run.\n    67→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:60:No existing gate asks this because the gate infrastructure was designed for document pipelines where a document's existence and structure are reliable proxies for the work that produced it. For an executor that dispatches to real step implementations, those proxies break when the dispatch mechanism is absent.\n    68→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:76:  - prompts-executor-design\n    69→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:180:A minimal skill used exclusively for smoke testing the cli-portify executor.\n    70→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:235:| `return-contract.yaml` | executor (always) | Must exist |\n    71→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:241:SMOKE_TEST_GATE FAILED: intermediate-artifact-absence\n    72→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:291:SMOKE_TEST_GATE FAILED: content-evidence-absent\n    73→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:321:The forensic report establishes the key observable: the no-op run completes in milliseconds. Specifically, the executor races through 12 steps with `(0, \"\", False)` returns and writes `return-contract.yaml` with no I/O beyond that single file write. Wall-clock time is under 1 second.\n    74→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:337:| `SMOKE_STEP_TIMEOUT_S` | 120 seconds | Per-step timeout passed to the executor. Consistent with existing `turn_budget` parameters in the executor. |\n    75→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:351:The timing check is the fastest-failing check. It runs first. If it fails, artifact checks are skipped and the gate fails immediately with diagnosis pointing to the no-op executor pattern.\n    76→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:353:The no-op ceiling (5 seconds) is conservative: even if CI environments are slow, a no-op executor cannot take 5 seconds unless the machine is severely under load. If a CI machine is so slow that a no-op takes 5 seconds, all other timeouts will be proportionally exceeded and the run will fail anyway.\n    77→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:359:**CPU**: The smoke run is single-process with subprocess invocations for Claude steps. No parallel execution constraint beyond what the executor already manages.\n    78→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:434:**Point 1: Pre-release check in the sprint executor**\n    79→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:436:Before `superclaude sprint` can mark a cli-portify release task as complete, the sprint executor must verify the smoke gate has passed. This integrates with the unified-audit-gating v1.2.1 `audit_release_passed` state transition. Concretely: the release task enters `ready_for_audit_release`, the smoke gate runs, and only `audit_release_passed` permits transition to `released`.\n    80→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:487:**AC-001**: Given the no-op executor (step_runner=None), the smoke gate must fail with `check_name=\"execution_time\"` when elapsed time is under `SMOKE_NOOP_CEILING_S`.\n    81→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:505:As a standalone validation, run the gate against the known-bad executor (with `step_runner` not provided) and verify exit code is non-zero and the gate report contains at least one `SMOKE_TEST_GATE FAILED` entry. This regression check must be included in the CI test suite as a permanently-preserved test case documenting the exact bug class the gate was designed to catch.\n    82→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:605:SMOKE_TEST_GATE (G-012) FAILED\n    83→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/proposal-04-smoke-test-gate.md:610:FAILED CHECKS:\n    84→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:5:**Reference incident**: cli-portify executor no-op bug — shipped across v2.24, v2.24.1, v2.25 with\n    85→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:53:`sprint/executor.py:47-90`), and `TrailingGateRunner` (never called from `execute_sprint()`).\n    86→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:104:| 8–9 | Reuses existing patterns with minor extensions; integrates with pipeline executor cleanly |\n    87→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:106:| 4–5 | Requires new hook points in executor but doesn't conflict with existing gates |\n    88→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:114:- `sprint/executor.py:47-90` — `SprintGatePolicy` stub; integration hook candidates at lines 668–787\n    89→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/scoring-framework.md:168:   `executor.py:393` during static analysis.\"\n    90→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/final-ranking.md:6:**Reference incident**: cli-portify executor no-op bug — shipped across v2.24, v2.24.1, v2.25\n    91→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/final-ranking.md:44:sprint executor covers two additional \"defined but not wired\" instances from the forensic report.\n    92→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/final-ranking.md:150:tie with Proposal 02. NOPF would have directly fingerprinted `executor.py:397-399`; CPC would have\n    93→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/final-ranking.md:242:**Proposal 05**: Deploy `SilentSuccessDetector` as a post-execution hook in `executor.run()`.\n    94→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/final-ranking.md:246:- Additive changes: `executor.py` (+20 lines), `models.py` (+10 lines)\n    95→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:5:**Reference incident**: cli-portify executor no-op bug (v2.24 – v2.25)\n    96→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:24:Proposal 05 is the most direct solution to the exact failure mode documented in the forensic report. Every other proposal in this suite — static analysis, fidelity hardening, smoke tests — operates at some remove from the production execution path. This proposal operates inside the production execution path itself, wrapping the executor's existing step loop with a post-completion audit that requires no external toolchain, no LLM call, and no separate test harness.\n    97→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:34:[Omitted long matching line]\n    98→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:42:[Omitted long matching line]\n    99→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:44:The proposal's own scoring assessment of 7.70 is conservative. On the Catch Rate axis, the score should be 10: the detection is deterministic, not probabilistic. The composite lands in Tier 1 (Implement Immediately) by any fair reading of the framework. The ~530 lines of new code is a one-time cost; the protection is permanent and applies to every pipeline run for the lifetime of the executor.\n   100→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:56:[Omitted long matching line]\n   101→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:68:[Omitted long matching line]\n   102→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:157:**Recommended resolution**: Implement Proposal 05 Phase 1 (detector core + executor instrumentation) immediately, in parallel with Proposal 04. Do not wait for Proposals 03 and 04 to be validated before deploying the runtime safety net. Once all three proposals are deployed, re-evaluate whether Proposal 05's thresholds and weight assignments should be recalibrated based on observed production data.\n   103→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:181:[Omitted long matching line]\n   104→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:183:[Omitted long matching line]\n   105→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:185:**Note**: The scoring framework's Axis 2 definition requires 8+ to address \"at least two\" of the three other named instances. This proposal describes applicability to the sprint executor but does not specify the implementation. Score of 7 reflects \"catches 2 other named bug classes with described (not implemented) coverage.\"\n   106→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:195:- `executor.py`: ~20 lines additive changes\n   107→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:215:[Omitted long matching line]\n   108→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:223:**Evidence**: The proposal integrates as a post-loop hook in `executor.run()`, before `_emit_return_contract()`. This is a clean integration point. The existing gate infrastructure (`GateCriteria`, `ALL_GATES`, `gate_passed()`) does not need modification — the detector runs inside the executor, not through the gate dispatch pipeline. The `GateResult` schema integration is deferred to Phase 2, which is appropriate.\n   109→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:225:[Omitted long matching line]\n   110→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:256:| Generalizability | 25% | 7 | 1.75 | Applies to sprint executor and future pipeline executors; requires per-executor instrumentation; covers 2 of 3 named forensic instances with described (not implemented) coverage |\n   111→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:259:| Integration Fit | 15% | 7 | 1.05 | Clean executor hook; not expressed as `GateCriteria`; `silent_success_audit` is a side-channel until Phase 2 GateResult integration |\n   112→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:264:Note: The proposal's own self-assessment of 7.70 places it in Tier 1. The debate's adjusted score of 7.30 places it at the top of Tier 2, close to the Tier 1 boundary. The 0.40 gap is attributable to two downward adjustments: Catch Rate from 10 to 9 (FN2 partial detection scenario) and Integration Fit from 8 to 7 (executor hook vs gate registration). Both adjustments are evidence-driven.\n   113→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:276:**Condition 1 — Immediate**: Deploy Phase 1 (detector core, executor instrumentation, `test_no_op_pipeline_scores_1_0`) immediately, in parallel with Proposal 04 development. Rationale: until Proposals 03 and 04 are deployed and validated, the production path has zero no-op detection. Proposal 05 Phase 1 closes this gap at 3 days of implementation cost (detector + executor changes + smoke tests; documentation and gate integration deferred).\n   114→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-05-silent-success-detection.md:280:**Condition 3 — Phase 2 (with v1.2.1 Phase 1)**: Integrate `SilentSuccessResult` as a `GateResult` in the `ALL_GATES` registry. Until this is done, the detector is a private executor concern, not a first-class gate. Phase 2 integration raises the Integration Fit score to 8 and the composite to 7.45 (Tier 1 boundary).\n   115→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:6:**Incident context**: `docs/generated/cli-portify-executor-noop-forensic-report.md`\n   116→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:49:  consumer: \"src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/executor.py\"\n   117→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:55:The Phase A programmatic check for WIRE-002 scans the AST of `executor.py` for a call to\n   118→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:57:such call. The check would have returned `passed=False` with evidence `executor.py:1395`.\n   119→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:70:2. `SprintGatePolicy` — stub at `sprint/executor.py:47-90`, never invoked from `execute_sprint()`.\n   120→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:86:at `sprint/executor.py:47-90` is already the designated integration hook — it just needs to be\n   121→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-link3-code-fidelity.md:136:executor = PortifyExecutor(steps=steps, ..., step_runner=_real_step_runner)\n   122→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/proposals/debate-01-li