{"parentUuid":"c2d90ed9-7721-4b01-8a61-6ef8d74362cf","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"c899109a-85f0-4ce2-8d4b-537fc48bb9f2","agentId":"adc6e872310c3ca7e","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_HuJtlRWuqxerfXxubCf2NL4L","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/return-contract.yaml:7:fallback_mode: false\n     2→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:83:[Omitted long matching line]\n     3→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:124:| **Prompt constraint for integration enumeration** | V1-D + V5-2 merged | Prevention-layer reduces generation-time omissions | D1 (prevention reduces bug frequency before detection runs) | Modify `build_generate_prompt()` in prompts.py. ~50 lines of prompt text. |\n     4→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:132:| **Manifest + obligation ledger injection** | V3-2 + V2-B merged | Prevention layer; requires state management between pipeline steps | Phase 2, alongside coherence graph (shares extraction infrastructure) |\n     5→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:172:        \"undischarged_obligations\",    # V2-A\n     6→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:179:            name=\"no_undischarged_obligations\",\n     7→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:180:            check_fn=_no_undischarged_obligations,    # V2-A\n     8→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:181:            failure_message=\"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected\",\n     9→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:198:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_scanner.py` (V2-A, ~200 LOC)\n    10→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:205:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` (wire gate after merge, add structural audit after extract)\n    11→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/base-selection.md:206:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py` (add integration enumeration block)\n    12→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:20:[Omitted long matching line]\n    13→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:26:V1 and V4 are the most structurally complete documents with explicit file tables, open questions, and per-solution confidence ratings. V2 has the most operationally detailed implementation (the obligation scanner is nearly production-ready code). V3 is the most architecturally grounded, mapping extensively to existing pipeline infrastructure. V5 has the most thorough taxonomy of the problem space (7-category integration mechanism table) but the fewest solutions.\n    14→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:77:| C-038 | Implicit obligation loss | -- | A, B, C, D (primary) | 2 (manifest) | -- | -- |\n    15→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:125:[Omitted long matching line]\n    16→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:129:[Omitted long matching line]\n    17→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:142:| U-004 | V2 | **Obligation ledger as pipeline state (Solution B)**: Accumulates deferred commitments across phases and injects them into subsequent prompts | V3-2's manifest injection tracks deliverables (what was built) but not obligations (what was promised for later). The obligation ledger is the inverse. | HIGH efficacy: preventive rather than detective. MEDIUM implementability: requires state management and prompt injection. |\n    18→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:143:| U-005 | V3 | **Mapping to existing dataflow infrastructure**: Identifies 5 existing modules (dataflow_graph.py, dataflow_pass.py, deliverables.py, conflict_detector.py, contract_extractor.py) that provide architectural precedent | No other variant maps to existing non-gate infrastructure. V1/V4/V5 reference only gates.py and executor.py. | HIGH implementability: reduces implementation risk by building on proven patterns. |\n    19→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:159:[Omitted long matching line]\n    20→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:162:[Omitted long matching line]\n    21→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:164:| A-006 | **A single point of gate insertion (post-merge, pre-fidelity) is architecturally stable** | 12 of 16 solutions assume this insertion point exists and will persist. | The pipeline step ordering is defined in executor.py and could be refactored. If steps are reordered, parallelized, or the fidelity check is moved, gate insertion points shift. | Solutions need re-wiring. Low-cost fix but adds maintenance burden. | LOW |\n    22→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:168:[Omitted long matching line]\n    23→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:198:| 9 | V4-5 (Requirement registry) | High | Stateful JSON artifact, state machine transitions, requires every pipeline step to participate. Architectural change. |\n    24→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:227:- **V2**: Scaffold-discharge vocabulary and obligation ledger -- the only deferred-commitment tracker\n    25→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/diff-analysis.md:244:| P4 | Deliverable manifest + obligation ledger injection | V2-B + V3-2 merged | Prevention | Likely (70%) |\n    26→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:14:When an LLM generates a multi-phase roadmap, it frequently writes early-phase milestones that contain **scaffolding language**: \"mocked steps\", \"skeleton executor\", \"placeholder dispatch\", \"stub implementation\". Each of these phrases creates an **implicit obligation** -- a deferred commitment that some later phase must replace the scaffold with real implementation.\n    27→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:16:Humans track these obligations mentally (\"I need to wire that up in Phase 4\"). LLMs do not maintain a running ledger of deferred commitments. By the time the agent generates Phase 4-7 content, the Phase 2 scaffolding decision has fallen out of active attention. The context window contains the prompt for the current phase and possibly the extraction document, but not a structured record of \"things earlier phases promised that you must now fulfill.\"\n    28→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:24:3. **The obligation is implicit, not explicit.** The word \"mocked\" implies a future replacement, but no explicit task item says \"Phase N: replace Phase 2 mocks with real dispatch.\"\n    29→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:40:[Omitted long matching line]\n    30→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:50:None of these checks detect the pattern: \"Phase N uses scaffolding language that creates an obligation no later phase discharges.\"\n    31→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:64:New module: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_scanner.py`\n    32→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:67:\"\"\"Obligation scanner -- detects undischarged scaffolding obligations in roadmaps.\n    33→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:70:scaffold, temporary, hardcoded) that create implicit obligations, then verifies\n    34→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:71:each obligation has a corresponding discharge term (replace, wire, integrate,\n    35→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:85:# Terms that CREATE an obligation (something deferred)\n    36→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:100:# Terms that DISCHARGE an obligation (something fulfilled)\n    37→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:120:    \"\"\"A detected scaffolding obligation.\"\"\"\n    38→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:132:    \"\"\"Result of obligation scanning.\"\"\"\n    39→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:133:    total_obligations: int\n    40→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:136:    obligations: list[Obligation]\n    41→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:143:def scan_obligations(content: str) -> ObligationReport:\n    42→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:144:    \"\"\"Scan roadmap content for scaffolding obligations and discharge status.\n    43→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:152:    4. Report undischarged obligations.\n    44→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:157:    obligations: list[Obligation] = []\n    45→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:186:            obligations.append(Obligation(\n    46→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:196:    undischarged_count = sum(1 for o in obligations if not o.discharged)\n    47→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:198:        total_obligations=len(obligations),\n    48→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:199:        discharged=len(obligations) - undischarged_count,\n    49→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:201:        obligations=obligations,\n    50→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:279:def _no_undischarged_obligations(content: str) -> bool:\n    51→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:280:    \"\"\"Verify all scaffolding obligations in early phases are discharged by later phases.\"\"\"\n    52→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:281:    from .obligation_scanner import scan_obligations\n    53→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:282:    report = scan_obligations(content)\n    54→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:287:    name=\"no_undischarged_obligations\",\n    55→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:288:    check_fn=_no_undischarged_obligations,\n    56→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:289:    failure_message=\"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected: early-phase mocks/stubs/skeletons have no corresponding replace/integrate/wire task in later phases\",\n    57→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:293:**How this catches the cli-portify bug**: The merged roadmap contains Phase 2 with \"mocked steps\" and Phases 4-7 without any discharge term (\"replace mock\", \"wire into skeleton\", \"integrate with executor\"). The scanner finds \"mocked\" in Phase 2, searches Phases 3-7 for a discharge referencing the same component, finds none, and reports an undischarged obligation. The `MERGE_GATE` fails with an actionable error message.\n    58→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:299:**Approach**: Maintain a structured JSON ledger that accumulates obligations as phases are generated. Inject the ledger into subsequent phase prompts so the LLM is aware of outstanding commitments.\n    59→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:303:New file created by the pipeline: `<output_dir>/obligation-ledger.json`\n    60→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:308:  \"obligations\": [\n    61→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:323:**Pipeline changes** (in `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py`):\n    62→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:325:1. After each `generate-*` step completes, run the obligation scanner on the output.\n    63→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:326:2. Append any new obligations to `obligation-ledger.json` in the output directory.\n    64→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:340:4. After each subsequent step, re-scan to check if new content discharges any open obligations. Update ledger status to \"DISCHARGED\" with the phase and task that discharged it.\n    65→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:342:**Prompt injection point**: Modify `build_generate_prompt()` and `build_merge_prompt()` in `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py` to accept an optional `obligation_ledger: str | None` parameter. When non-None, append it to the prompt.\n    66→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:345:- Preventive, not just detective. The LLM sees the obligations *while generating* later phases.\n    67→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:351:- The obligation extraction from phase output requires either regex (imprecise) or an LLM call (expensive, non-deterministic).\n    68→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:357:**Approach**: After the merge step, run a dedicated validation LLM call that receives the full roadmap and a structured prompt asking it to identify all scaffolding obligations and verify each is discharged.\n    69→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:362:# In executor.py, add a new step:\n    70→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:364:    id=\"obligation-check\",\n    71→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:365:    output_file=output_dir / \"obligation-check.md\",\n    72→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:375:def build_obligation_check_prompt(merged_roadmap_path: Path) -> str:\n    73→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:379:        \"where an early phase creates a scaffolding obligation (uses terms like \"\n    74→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:382:        \"contains an explicit task to discharge that obligation (uses terms like \"\n    75→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:386:        \"- total_obligations: (integer) count of scaffolding obligations found\\n\"\n    76→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:392:        \"For undischarged obligations, Discharge Phase and Task should be '[MISSING]'.\\n\\n\"\n    77→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:398:- Can catch subtle obligations that regex misses (e.g., \"defer X to later\" without explicit scaffold vocabulary).\n    78→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:402:- Non-deterministic (LLM may miss obligations or hallucinate them).\n    79→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:410:**Approach**: Run Solution A (deterministic regex scanner) first. If it finds zero obligations (possible false negative -- the roadmap uses unusual vocabulary for scaffolding), run Solution C (LLM call) as a fallback. If Solution A finds obligations and all are discharged, skip the LLM call.\n    80→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:422:1. Create `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_scanner.py` with the `scan_obligations()` function and vocabulary constants.\n    81→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:423:2. Add `_no_undischarged_obligations` semantic check to `MERGE_GATE` in `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py`.\n    82→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:424:3. Write tests in `tests/roadmap/test_obligation_scanner.py` covering:\n    83→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:428:   - Multiple obligations, some discharged and some not (should fail)\n    84→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:432:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_scanner.py` (new)\n    85→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:434:- `tests/roadmap/test_obligation_scanner.py` (new)\n    86→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:446:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_ledger.py` (new)\n    87→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:447:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` (add ledger accumulation hooks)\n    88→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:448:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py` (add ledger injection to prompt builders)\n    89→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:485:2. The `MERGE_GATE` runs `_no_undischarged_obligations` as a semantic check.\n    90→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:486:3. `scan_obligations()` finds \"mocked\" in Phase 2, extracts component context \"executor\" / \"steps\".\n    91→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:488:5. The obligation is marked `discharged=False`.\n    92→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:490:7. The `MERGE_GATE` **fails** with message: *\"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected: early-phase mocks/stubs/skeletons have no corresponding replace/integrate/wire task in later phases\"*.\n    93→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:492:   - Re-runs the merge with explicit instructions to address the obligation, or\n    94→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:503:| False positives: scaffold terms used descriptively (\"the test uses mocks\") | MEDIUM | Add context-aware filtering: ignore terms inside code blocks, test descriptions, or after \"test\" keywords. Allow `# obligation-exempt` comment to suppress. |\n    95→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:504:| False negatives: unusual vocabulary (\"defer this to later\") | LOW | Solution D (LLM fallback) catches these. Solution A vocabulary can be extended over time. |\n    96→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md:519:The obligation scanner infrastructure (phase splitting, term matching, cross-phase reference checking) could be extended to catch these related patterns.\n    97→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:12:- V2-Advocate (Implicit Obligation) -- primary: Solution A (obligation scanner)\n    98→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:35:**Steelmanning V2**: The scaffold-discharge vocabulary (V2-A) catches a genuinely different failure class -- undischarged deferred commitments -- that ID cross-referencing misses entirely. The obligation concept is formally distinct from the omission concept. A roadmap that mentions FR-047 in a throwaway sentence passes V1-A but still fails V2-A if the scaffold was never discharged.\n    99→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:47:[Omitted long matching line]\n   100→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:49:**Strongest arguments for V2 primary (obligation scanner)**:\n   101→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:53:2. **Nearly production-ready code**: The obligation scanner in the proposal is ~200 LOC of fully specified Python with scaffold/discharge term vocabularies, phase splitting logic, component context extraction, and a clean `ObligationReport` dataclass. It is the most implementation-ready code of any proposal.\n   102→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:83:**Steelmanning V2**: The obligation scanner addresses a specific failure mode -- undischarged scaffolding -- that the coherence graph handles awkwardly. A scaffold term like \"mocked\" is a linguistic signal, not a producer-consumer relationship. The graph can detect that steps are produced but never consumed by the executor, but it cannot detect that the word \"mocked\" in Phase 2 creates an expectation that V2 explicitly tracks.\n   103→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:103:**Steelmanning V2**: The obligation scanner catches a class of bugs (undischarged scaffolding) that V4's fingerprint checker misses entirely. If a roadmap says \"mocked steps\" in Phase 2 and never discharges them, V4 would only catch this if \"mocked\" happens to be a fingerprint identifier (it likely is not, since it is a description, not a code identifier). V2's scaffold vocabulary is a specialized tool for a specialized failure mode.\n   104→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:113:[Omitted long matching line]\n   105→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:127:**Steelmanning V2**: The obligation scanner is simpler and catches a complementary failure mode. A roadmap with \"mocked steps\" that is never discharged does not look like a contract violation -- the mock is not a dispatch table, registry, or injection point. V2 catches linguistic promises; V5 catches structural omissions.\n   106→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:175:[Omitted long matching line]\n   107→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:179:V5-1 is mechanism-aware, which is more precise than V2-A for dispatch-table-type bugs. But mechanism-awareness is also a limitation: V5's `DISPATCH_PATTERNS` only fires on dispatch tables, registries, injection points, and routing tables. A scaffold obligation that is not one of these 7 categories (e.g., \"hardcoded configuration values\" or \"temporary file paths\") would be missed by V5 but caught by V2-A's vocabulary.\n   108→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:283:**V5 final position**: The anti-pattern rule engine (V5-3) should house V2-A's scaffold logic as one rule (AP-001 delegates to the obligation scanner). This gives V2's detection the organizational home of V5's extensible framework.\n   109→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:310:| D1: Efficacy (0.35) | 7 | Catches the cli-portify bug with ~85% confidence (\"mocked steps\" is a clear scaffold term, no discharge found). Misses cases where scaffolding uses non-standard vocabulary. Does not catch pure omissions (requirement absent entirely vs. obligation undischarged). |\n   110→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/debate-transcript.md:387:- **V3-2 (Manifest injection)**: Consider merging with V2-B (obligation ledger) into a single \"prior phase context\" injection block for generation prompts. Prevention-layer complement to detection-layer solutions.\n   111→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:29:- **Module dependency graph**: `executor.py --> steps/validate_config.py`, `executor.py --> steps/discover_components.py`, etc.\n   112→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:35:> \"Implement executor: sequential execution only, `--dry-run`, `--resume <step-id>`, signal handling\"\n   113→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:40:The three-way dispatch, `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS`, module dependency graph, and integration test were all silently dropped. The roadmap produced a plausible-looking executor phase that addressed infrastructure concerns (dry-run, resume, signals) while omitting the core wiring that makes steps execute real work.\n   114→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:158:Modify `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` to run the cross-reference check after the spec-fidelity step produces its output but before the gate is evaluated. If missing IDs are found, inject them as HIGH severity deviations into the fidelity report frontmatter before the gate reads it. This sidesteps the `SemanticCheck(check_fn: Callable[[str], bool])` single-argument limitation.\n   115→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:161:# In executor.py, after spec-fidelity step completes but before gate check:\n   116→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:361:# New prompt in src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py\n   117→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:566:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` — Add pre-gate cross-reference check after spec-fidelity step\n   118→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:588:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py` — Add `build_negative_space_prompt()`\n   119→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:589:- `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` — Add `negative-space` step to pipeline\n   120→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:622:| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/prompts.py` | Negative-space prompt builder | New function |\n   121→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:624:| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` | Pre-gate cross-reference check | Modify existing |\n   122→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/04-self-audit-blindness-mitigation.md:642:5. **How do we handle specs that don't use formal IDs?** Layer 1 provides no value for such specs. Layer 2 (fingerprints) is the fallback, but its threshold needs to be lenient enough to avoid false positives on loosely-structured specs. Should we make the ID cross-reference check conditional on the extraction reporting `> 0` formal IDs?\n   123→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:28:- **Source**: V2, `02-implicit-obligation-tracking.md`, Solution A (lines 58-274)\n   124→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:31:- **After**: Code adopted nearly verbatim from V2-A proposal. Gate integration redirected from `MERGE_GATE` to new `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`. Added vocabulary management table from V2 Section 5. Added false positive mitigation subsection per refactor-plan Section 6 Weakness 1 (component context extraction, code-block treatment, `# obligation-exempt` escape hatch).\n   125→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:32:- **Provenance**: `<!-- Source: V2-A (obligation scanner) -->`\n   126→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:180:| Section 4 references V2-A | `obligation_scanner.py` code present | RESOLVED |\n   127→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:210:| Section 4 | `<!-- Source: V2-A (obligation scanner) -->` |\n   128→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/merge-log.md:226:- **Changes from V2 (co-base)**: 1 (obligation scanner)\n   129→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/01-completeness-bias-mitigation.md:44:Plus a `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS` dictionary mapping step IDs to real Python functions, a module dependency graph (`executor.py --> steps/validate_config.py`, etc.), and an integration test `test_programmatic_step_routing`.\n   130→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/01-completeness-bias-mitigation.md:50:> \"Implement executor: sequential execution only, --dry-run, --resume <step-id>, signal handling\"\n   131→.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/adversarial/01-completeness-bias-mitigation.md:56:Zero mentions of `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS`, three